# Building a Simple Data Structure in Rust: Comprehensive Documentation for Beginners

Understanding how to build custom data structures in Rust is like learning to **design and construct specialized storage and organization systems for your professional restaurant chain** - you need to create efficient, safe, and reliable systems that can store, organize, and manage data (ingredients, orders, customer information) without any risk of corruption, loss, or unsafe access. Just as a professional restaurant manager must design storage systems that ensure food safety, prevent contamination, and allow efficient access by staff, building data structures in Rust means creating systems that ensure memory safety, prevent data races, and provide efficient operations while leveraging Rust's ownership system for automatic resource management.

## The Professional Restaurant Storage System Design Analogy üè™

### Imagine You're Designing Custom Storage Solutions for Your Restaurant Chain

**The Problem with Unsafe Storage Systems:**

```rust
// ‚ùå Unsafe approach - like having uncontrolled access to storage
// Multiple people can access same storage simultaneously
// No tracking of who has what
// Risk of data corruption and unsafe access
```

**The Power of Rust's Safe Data Structures - Professional Storage Management:**

```rust
// ‚úÖ Safe approach - controlled access with clear ownership
struct SafeStorage<T> {
    items: Vec<T>,
    capacity: usize,
}

impl<T> SafeStorage<T> {
    fn new(capacity: usize) -> Self {
        SafeStorage {
            items: Vec::new(),
            capacity,
        }
    }

    fn store(&mut self, item: T) -> Result<(), &'static str> {
        if self.items.len() < self.capacity {
            self.items.push(item);
            Ok(())
        } else {
            Err("Storage full")
        }
    }

    fn retrieve(&mut self) -> Option<T> {
        self.items.pop()
    }
}
// Clear ownership, safe access, automatic cleanup!
```

**Why Building Safe Data Structures Is Critical:**

- üõ°Ô∏è **Memory safety** - No dangling pointers, use-after-free, or data corruption
- ‚ö° **Performance** - Zero-cost abstractions with compile-time optimizations
- üîí **Thread safety** - Clear ownership prevents data races
- üéØ **Predictable behavior** - Compile-time guarantees about resource management
- üìà **Scalable design** - Patterns that work from simple to complex systems


## Understanding Data Structure Fundamentals in Rust

### The Safe Memory Management Foundation

**Rust's ownership system provides the foundation for building safe data structures:**

```rust
fn demonstrate_data_structure_fundamentals() {
    println!("üèóÔ∏è Data Structure Fundamentals - Safe Memory Management Foundation");
    println!("{:=<75}", "");

    // Building data structures in Rust is like designing professional storage systems
    println!("üìã Rust Data Structure Core Concepts:");
    println!("   üè† Ownership - Each value has exactly one owner");
    println!("   üì¶ Box<T> - Heap allocation for recursive structures");
    println!("   ‚ùì Option<T> - Safe representation of optional values");
    println!("   üîÑ Borrowing - Temporary access without ownership transfer");
    println!("   ‚ö° Zero-cost abstractions - No runtime overhead for safety");

    // Example 1: Basic Structure Design Principles
    println!("\n1Ô∏è‚É£ Basic Structure Design Principles:");

    // Simple storage container demonstrating ownership
    struct IngredientStorage {
        name: String,
        items: Vec<String>,
        max_capacity: usize,
    }

    impl IngredientStorage {
        fn new(name: String, max_capacity: usize) -> Self {
            println!("     üèóÔ∏è Creating storage: {}", name);
            IngredientStorage {
                name,
                items: Vec::new(),
                max_capacity,
            }
        }

        fn add_ingredient(&mut self, ingredient: String) -> Result<(), String> {
            if self.items.len() >= self.max_capacity {
                return Err(format!("Storage {} is full", self.name));
            }

            println!("     üì¶ Adding {} to {}", ingredient, self.name);
            self.items.push(ingredient);
            Ok(())
        }

        fn get_ingredient(&mut self) -> Option<String> {
            match self.items.pop() {
                Some(ingredient) => {
                    println!("     üì§ Retrieved {} from {}", ingredient, self.name);
                    Some(ingredient)
                }
                None => {
                    println!("     ‚ùå Storage {} is empty", self.name);
                    None
                }
            }
        }

        fn count(&self) -> usize {
            self.items.len()
        }
    }

    // Demonstrate ownership and borrowing
    let mut vegetable_storage = IngredientStorage::new("Vegetable Storage".to_string(), 5);

    // Add ingredients (ownership transferred to storage)
    vegetable_storage.add_ingredient("Tomatoes".to_string()).ok();
    vegetable_storage.add_ingredient("Lettuce".to_string()).ok();
    vegetable_storage.add_ingredient("Carrots".to_string()).ok();

    println!("     üìä Current storage has {} items", vegetable_storage.count());

    // Retrieve ingredients (ownership transferred from storage)
    if let Some(ingredient) = vegetable_storage.get_ingredient() {
        println!("     üçΩÔ∏è Using ingredient: {}", ingredient);
        // ingredient is automatically cleaned up here
    }

    println!("     üìä After retrieval: {} items remaining", vegetable_storage.count());

    // Example 2: Generic Data Structures
    println!("\n2Ô∏è‚É£ Generic Data Structures - Universal Storage Systems:");

    // Generic storage that works with any type
    struct UniversalStorage<T> {
        items: Vec<T>,
        name: String,
    }

    impl<T> UniversalStorage<T>
    where T: std::fmt::Debug {
        fn new(name: String) -> Self {
            UniversalStorage {
                items: Vec::new(),
                name,
            }
        }

        fn store(&mut self, item: T) {
            println!("     üì¶ Storing {:?} in {}", item, self.name);
            self.items.push(item);
        }

        fn retrieve(&mut self) -> Option<T> {
            match self.items.pop() {
                Some(item) => {
                    println!("     üì§ Retrieved {:?} from {}", item, self.name);
                    Some(item)
                }
                None => None,
            }
        }

        fn peek(&self) -> Option<&T> {
            self.items.last()
        }

        fn len(&self) -> usize {
            self.items.len()
        }
    }

    // Use generic storage with different types
    let mut number_storage = UniversalStorage::new("Number Storage".to_string());
    let mut order_storage = UniversalStorage::new("Order Storage".to_string());

    // Store different types
    number_storage.store(42);
    number_storage.store(100);

    order_storage.store("Pizza Order #1".to_string());
    order_storage.store("Pasta Order #2".to_string());

    // Demonstrate borrowing with peek
    if let Some(top_number) = number_storage.peek() {
        println!("     üëÅÔ∏è Top number (borrowed): {}", top_number);
        // number_storage still owns the value
    }

    if let Some(top_order) = order_storage.peek() {
        println!("     üëÅÔ∏è Top order (borrowed): {}", top_order);
        // order_storage still owns the value
    }

    // Demonstrate ownership transfer
    if let Some(retrieved_number) = number_storage.retrieve() {
        println!("     üéØ Retrieved number (owned): {}", retrieved_number);
        // retrieved_number is owned by this scope now
    }

    // Example 3: Memory Safety Demonstrations
    println!("\n3Ô∏è‚É£ Memory Safety Demonstrations:");

    println!("   üõ°Ô∏è Rust prevents common memory safety issues:");

    // Demonstrate that Rust prevents use-after-free
    {
        let mut temp_storage = UniversalStorage::new("Temp Storage".to_string());
        temp_storage.store("Temporary item".to_string());
        println!("     ‚úÖ Temporary storage created and used safely");
    } // temp_storage automatically cleaned up here

    // Demonstrate that Rust prevents double-free through ownership
    let important_data = "Critical restaurant data".to_string();
    let mut secure_storage = UniversalStorage::new("Secure Storage".to_string());
    secure_storage.store(important_data); // Ownership transferred
    // important_data can no longer be used - Rust prevents accidental reuse

    println!("     ‚úÖ Data safely transferred to secure storage");

    println!("\nüéØ Data Structure Design Benefits:");
    println!("   üè† Clear ownership prevents memory leaks and corruption");
    println!("   üì¶ Generic design enables code reuse across different data types");
    println!("   üîí Borrowing allows safe temporary access without ownership transfer");
    println!("   ‚ö° Zero runtime cost - all safety checks happen at compile time");
    println!("   üõ°Ô∏è Impossible to create dangling pointers or use-after-free bugs");
}

fn main() {
    demonstrate_data_structure_fundamentals();
}
```


## Building a Complete Linked List Implementation

![Components of a Safe Linked List in Rust](data:image/png;base64,)

Components of a Safe Linked List in Rust

**Step-by-step construction of a safe, efficient linked list:**

```rust
fn demonstrate_complete_linked_list() {
    println!("üîó Complete Linked List Implementation - Professional Sequential Storage");
    println!("{:=<75}", "");

    // A linked list is like a chain of storage containers, each pointing to the next
    println!("üìã Linked List Design Concepts:");
    println!("   üîó Sequential storage - Each node points to the next");
    println!("   üì¶ Box<T> - Heap allocation for recursive structure");
    println!("   ‚ùì Option<Box<T>> - Safe representation of 'next' pointer");
    println!("   üè† Ownership chain - Each node owns the next node");

    // Step 1: Define the Node structure
    #[derive(Debug, Clone)]
    struct Node<T> {
        data: T,
        next: Option<Box<Node<T>>>,
    }

    impl<T> Node<T> {
        fn new(data: T) -> Self {
            Node {
                data,
                next: None,
            }
        }
    }

    // Step 2: Define the LinkedList structure
    struct LinkedList<T> {
        head: Option<Box<Node<T>>>,
        size: usize,
    }

    impl<T> LinkedList<T>
    where T: std::fmt::Debug + Clone {
        // Constructor
        fn new() -> Self {
            println!("     üèóÔ∏è Creating new empty linked list");
            LinkedList {
                head: None,
                size: 0,
            }
        }

        // Add element to front (push)
        fn push_front(&mut self, data: T) {
            let new_node = Box::new(Node {
                data: data.clone(),
                next: self.head.take(), // Take ownership of current head
            });

            self.head = Some(new_node);
            self.size += 1;

            println!("     üì¶ Pushed {:?} to front, size now: {}", data, self.size);
        }

        // Remove element from front (pop)
        fn pop_front(&mut self) -> Option<T> {
            self.head.take().map(|node| {
                self.head = node.next;
                self.size -= 1;
                println!("     üì§ Popped {:?} from front, size now: {}", node.data, self.size);
                node.data
            })
        }

        // Add element to back (append)
        fn push_back(&mut self, data: T) {
            let new_node = Box::new(Node::new(data.clone()));

            match &mut self.head {
                None => {
                    self.head = Some(new_node);
                }
                Some(head) => {
                    let mut current = head;
                    // Traverse to the end
                    while current.next.is_some() {
                        current = current.next.as_mut().unwrap();
                    }
                    current.next = Some(new_node);
                }
            }

            self.size += 1;
            println!("     üì¶ Pushed {:?} to back, size now: {}", data, self.size);
        }

        // Find element
        fn contains(&self, target: &T) -> bool
        where T: PartialEq {
            let mut current = &self.head;

            while let Some(node) = current {
                if node.data == *target {
                    return true;
                }
                current = &node.next;
            }

            false
        }

        // Get element at index
        fn get(&self, index: usize) -> Option<&T> {
            if index >= self.size {
                return None;
            }

            let mut current = &self.head;
            let mut current_index = 0;

            while let Some(node) = current {
                if current_index == index {
                    return Some(&node.data);
                }
                current = &node.next;
                current_index += 1;
            }

            None
        }

        // Get size
        fn len(&self) -> usize {
            self.size
        }

        // Check if empty
        fn is_empty(&self) -> bool {
            self.size == 0
        }

        // Display the list
        fn display(&self) {
            print!("     üîó List contents: [");
            let mut current = &self.head;
            let mut first = true;

            while let Some(node) = current {
                if !first {
                    print!(" -> ");
                }
                print!("{:?}", node.data);
                current = &node.next;
                first = false;
            }
            println!("]");
        }

        // Iterator support
        fn iter(&self) -> ListIterator<T> {
            ListIterator {
                current: &self.head,
            }
        }
    }

    // Custom iterator for the linked list
    struct ListIterator<'a, T> {
        current: &'a Option<Box<Node<T>>>,
    }

    impl<'a, T> Iterator for ListIterator<'a, T> {
        type Item = &'a T;

        fn next(&mut self) -> Option<Self::Item> {
            match self.current {
                Some(node) => {
                    let data = &node.data;
                    self.current = &node.next;
                    Some(data)
                }
                None => None,
            }
        }
    }

    // Automatic cleanup when list goes out of scope
    impl<T> Drop for LinkedList<T> {
        fn drop(&mut self) {
            println!("     üßπ LinkedList being dropped, cleaning up {} nodes", self.size);
            // Rust automatically handles the recursive cleanup of Box<Node<T>>
        }
    }

    // Step 3: Demonstrate the linked list in action
    println!("\nüîó Linked List Demonstration:");

    let mut order_queue = LinkedList::new();

    // Add orders to the queue
    order_queue.push_back("Pizza Order #1".to_string());
    order_queue.push_back("Pasta Order #2".to_string());
    order_queue.push_back("Salad Order #3".to_string());

    order_queue.display();

    // Add urgent order to front
    order_queue.push_front("URGENT: VIP Order".to_string());
    order_queue.display();

    println!("     üìä Queue size: {}", order_queue.len());

    // Search for orders
    if order_queue.contains(&"Pizza Order #1".to_string()) {
        println!("     üîç Found Pizza Order #1 in queue");
    }

    // Access specific orders by index
    if let Some(order) = order_queue.get(1) {
        println!("     üìã Order at index 1: {}", order);
    }

    // Process orders (remove from front)
    while !order_queue.is_empty() {
        if let Some(order) = order_queue.pop_front() {
            println!("     üçΩÔ∏è Processing: {}", order);
            order_queue.display();
        }
    }

    println!("     ‚úÖ All orders processed, queue is now empty");

    // Step 4: Demonstrate iterator usage
    println!("\nüîÑ Iterator Demonstration:");

    let mut number_list = LinkedList::new();
    for i in 1..=5 {
        number_list.push_back(i * 10);
    }

    print!("     üî¢ Numbers using iterator: ");
    for number in number_list.iter() {
        print!("{} ", number);
    }
    println!();

    // Demonstrate functional programming with iterators
    let sum: i32 = number_list.iter().sum();
    println!("     ‚ûï Sum of all numbers: {}", sum);

    let doubled: Vec<i32> = number_list.iter().map(|&x| x * 2).collect();
    println!("     ‚úñÔ∏è Doubled numbers: {:?}", doubled);

    println!("\nüéØ Linked List Memory Safety Benefits:");
    println!("   üì¶ Box<T> ensures heap allocation and single ownership");
    println!("   ‚ùì Option<T> safely represents absence of next node");
    println!("   üîó Ownership chain prevents memory leaks and dangling pointers");
    println!("   üßπ Automatic cleanup when list goes out of scope");
    println!("   üîí Borrowing enables safe iteration without ownership transfer");

    // Memory safety demonstration
    {
        let temp_list = LinkedList::new();
        // temp_list automatically cleaned up here
    }
    println!("     ‚úÖ Temporary list safely created and destroyed");
}

fn main() {
    demonstrate_complete_linked_list();
}
```


## Advanced Data Structure Patterns

### Professional-Grade Storage System Architectures

**Sophisticated patterns for building complex, efficient data structures:**

```rust
fn demonstrate_advanced_data_structure_patterns() {
    println!("üöÄ Advanced Data Structure Patterns - Professional Storage Architectures");
    println!("{:=<75}", "");

    use std::collections::HashMap;
    use std::hash::Hash;
    use std::rc::{Rc, Weak};
    use std::cell::RefCell;

    // Advanced patterns are like sophisticated restaurant management systems
    println!("üèóÔ∏è Advanced Data Structure Design Patterns:");

    // Pattern 1: Reference Counting for Shared Ownership
    println!("\n1Ô∏è‚É£ Pattern: Reference Counting - Shared Resource Management:");

    // Restaurant menu item that can be referenced by multiple orders
    #[derive(Debug)]
    struct MenuItem {
        name: String,
        price: f64,
        ingredients: Vec<String>,
    }

    impl MenuItem {
        fn new(name: String, price: f64, ingredients: Vec<String>) -> Rc<Self> {
            Rc::new(MenuItem {
                name,
                price,
                ingredients,
            })
        }
    }

    #[derive(Debug)]
    struct Order {
        id: u32,
        items: Vec<Rc<MenuItem>>, // Shared ownership of menu items
        total: f64,
    }

    impl Order {
        fn new(id: u32) -> Self {
            Order {
                id,
                items: Vec::new(),
                total: 0.0,
            }
        }

        fn add_item(&mut self, item: Rc<MenuItem>) {
            self.total += item.price;
            println!("     üì¶ Added {} to order {} (${:.2})", item.name, self.id, item.price);
            self.items.push(item);
        }

        fn get_total(&self) -> f64 {
            self.total
        }
    }

    // Demonstrate shared ownership
    println!("   üçΩÔ∏è Shared menu item system:");

    let pizza = MenuItem::new(
        "Margherita Pizza".to_string(),
        15.99,
        vec!["dough".to_string(), "tomato".to_string(), "mozzarella".to_string()]
    );

    let pasta = MenuItem::new(
        "Spaghetti Carbonara".to_string(),
        13.50,
        vec!["pasta".to_string(), "eggs".to_string(), "cheese".to_string()]
    );

    // Multiple orders can share the same menu items
    let mut order1 = Order::new(101);
    let mut order2 = Order::new(102);

    // Both orders include pizza (shared ownership)
    order1.add_item(Rc::clone(&pizza));
    order1.add_item(Rc::clone(&pasta));

    order2.add_item(Rc::clone(&pizza)); // Same pizza item, shared

    println!("     üìä Order 1 total: ${:.2}", order1.get_total());
    println!("     üìä Order 2 total: ${:.2}", order2.get_total());
    println!("     üîó Pizza reference count: {}", Rc::strong_count(&pizza));
    println!("     üîó Pasta reference count: {}", Rc::strong_count(&pasta));

    // Pattern 2: Interior Mutability with RefCell
    println!("\n2Ô∏è‚É£ Pattern: Interior Mutability - Flexible Access Control:");

    #[derive(Debug)]
    struct Restaurant {
        name: String,
        tables: RefCell<HashMap<u32, String>>, // Interior mutability
        revenue: RefCell<f64>,
    }

    impl Restaurant {
        fn new(name: String) -> Self {
            Restaurant {
                name,
                tables: RefCell::new(HashMap::new()),
                revenue: RefCell::new(0.0),
            }
        }

        // Methods can mutate interior data even with &self
        fn reserve_table(&self, table_id: u32, customer_name: String) -> Result<(), String> {
            let mut tables = self.tables.borrow_mut();

            if tables.contains_key(&table_id) {
                return Err(format!("Table {} already reserved", table_id));
            }

            tables.insert(table_id, customer_name.clone());
            println!("     ü™ë Reserved table {} for {}", table_id, customer_name);
            Ok(())
        }

        fn complete_order(&self, amount: f64) {
            let mut revenue = self.revenue.borrow_mut();
            *revenue += amount;
            println!("     üí∞ Added ${:.2} to revenue, total now: ${:.2}", amount, *revenue);
        }

        fn get_revenue(&self) -> f64 {
            *self.revenue.borrow()
        }

        fn list_reservations(&self) {
            let tables = self.tables.borrow();
            println!("     üìã Current reservations:");
            for (table_id, customer) in tables.iter() {
                println!("       Table {}: {}", table_id, customer);
            }
        }
    }

    println!("   üè™ Restaurant with interior mutability:");

    let restaurant = Restaurant::new("Ocean View Bistro".to_string());

    // Multiple operations on shared restaurant
    restaurant.reserve_table(1, "Alice Johnson".to_string()).ok();
    restaurant.reserve_table(2, "Bob Smith".to_string()).ok();
    restaurant.complete_order(28.99);
    restaurant.complete_order(15.50);

    restaurant.list_reservations();
    println!("     üí∞ Total revenue: ${:.2}", restaurant.get_revenue());

    // Pattern 3: Weak References to Prevent Cycles
    println!("\n3Ô∏è‚É£ Pattern: Weak References - Cycle Prevention:");

    #[derive(Debug)]
    struct Manager {
        name: String,
        restaurant: RefCell<Option<Weak<Restaurant>>>, // Weak reference prevents cycle
        employees: RefCell<Vec<Rc<Employee>>>,
    }

    #[derive(Debug)]
    struct Employee {
        name: String,
        manager: RefCell<Option<Weak<Manager>>>, // Weak reference prevents cycle
    }

    impl Manager {
        fn new(name: String) -> Rc<Self> {
            Rc::new(Manager {
                name,
                restaurant: RefCell::new(None),
                employees: RefCell::new(Vec::new()),
            })
        }

        fn add_employee(self: &Rc<Self>, employee: Rc<Employee>) {
            *employee.manager.borrow_mut() = Some(Rc::downgrade(self));
            self.employees.borrow_mut().push(employee);
            println!("     üë• Manager {} added employee", self.name);
        }

        fn list_employees(&self) {
            let employees = self.employees.borrow();
            println!("     üëî Manager {} has {} employees:", self.name, employees.len());
            for employee in employees.iter() {
                println!("       - {}", employee.name);
            }
        }
    }

    impl Employee {
        fn new(name: String) -> Rc<Self> {
            Rc::new(Employee {
                name,
                manager: RefCell::new(None),
            })
        }

        fn get_manager_name(&self) -> Option<String> {
            self.manager
                .borrow()
                .as_ref()?
                .upgrade()
                .map(|manager| manager.name.clone())
        }
    }

    println!("   üë• Management hierarchy with weak references:");

    let manager = Manager::new("Alice Manager".to_string());
    let employee1 = Employee::new("Bob Employee".to_string());
    let employee2 = Employee::new("Carol Employee".to_string());

    manager.add_employee(Rc::clone(&employee1));
    manager.add_employee(Rc::clone(&employee2));

    manager.list_employees();

    if let Some(manager_name) = employee1.get_manager_name() {
        println!("     üë§ Bob's manager: {}", manager_name);
    }

    println!("     üîó Manager reference count: {}", Rc::strong_count(&manager));
    println!("     üîó Employee1 reference count: {}", Rc::strong_count(&employee1));

    // Pattern 4: Generic Cache with TTL
    println!("\n4Ô∏è‚É£ Pattern: Generic Cache - Time-Based Resource Management:");

    use std::time::{Duration, Instant};

    struct CacheEntry<T> {
        value: T,
        created_at: Instant,
    }

    struct TTLCache<K, V>
    where K: Hash + Eq {
        data: RefCell<HashMap<K, CacheEntry<V>>>,
        ttl: Duration,
        max_size: usize,
    }

    impl<K, V> TTLCache<K, V>
    where K: Hash + Eq + Clone, V: Clone {
        fn new(ttl: Duration, max_size: usize) -> Self {
            TTLCache {
                data: RefCell::new(HashMap::new()),
                ttl,
                max_size,
            }
        }

        fn insert(&self, key: K, value: V) {
            let mut data = self.data.borrow_mut();

            // Remove expired entries
            data.retain(|_, entry| entry.created_at.elapsed() < self.ttl);

            // Remove oldest if at capacity
            if data.len() >= self.max_size {
                if let Some(oldest_key) = data.keys().next().cloned() {
                    data.remove(&oldest_key);
                    println!("     üóëÔ∏è Evicted oldest cache entry");
                }
            }

            data.insert(key, CacheEntry {
                value,
                created_at: Instant::now(),
            });

            println!("     üíæ Cached entry, cache size: {}", data.len());
        }

        fn get(&self, key: &K) -> Option<V> {
            let mut data = self.data.borrow_mut();

            match data.get(key) {
                Some(entry) => {
                    if entry.created_at.elapsed() < self.ttl {
                        println!("     üìñ Cache hit for key");
                        Some(entry.value.clone())
                    } else {
                        println!("     ‚è∞ Cache entry expired");
                        data.remove(key);
                        None
                    }
                }
                None => {
                    println!("     ‚ùå Cache miss for key");
                    None
                }
            }
        }

        fn size(&self) -> usize {
            self.data.borrow().len()
        }
    }

    println!("   üíæ TTL Cache demonstration:");

    let cache = TTLCache::new(Duration::from_millis(100), 3);

    // Add items to cache
    cache.insert("menu_1", "Pizza Menu Data");
    cache.insert("menu_2", "Pasta Menu Data");
    cache.insert("menu_3", "Salad Menu Data");

    println!("     üìä Cache size: {}", cache.size());

    // Access cached items
    if let Some(data) = cache.get(&"menu_1") {
        println!("     ‚úÖ Retrieved: {}", data);
    }

    // Wait for expiration
    std::thread::sleep(Duration::from_millis(120));

    // Try to access expired item
    if cache.get(&"menu_1").is_none() {
        println!("     ‚è∞ Cache entry expired as expected");
    }

    println!("     üìä Cache size after expiration: {}", cache.size());

    println!("\nüéØ Advanced Pattern Benefits:");
    println!("   üîó Reference counting enables safe shared ownership");
    println!("   üîÑ Interior mutability allows flexible access patterns");
    println!("   üö´ Weak references prevent memory leak cycles");
    println!("   üíæ Generic caching provides reusable resource management");
    println!("   üõ°Ô∏è All patterns maintain Rust's memory safety guarantees");
}

fn main() {
    demonstrate_advanced_data_structure_patterns();
}
```

fn demonstrate_real_world_applications() {
    println!("üè¢ Real-World Applications - Complete Restaurant Management System");
    println!("{:=<75}", "");

    use std::collections::{HashMap, VecDeque};
    use std::rc::Rc;
    use std::cell::RefCell;

    // Real-world applications demonstrate data structures in complete systems
    println!("üíº Professional Data Structure Applications:");

    // Application 1: Order Priority Queue
    println!("\n1Ô∏è‚É£ Application: Priority Order Processing System");

    #[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq, Eq)]
    enum OrderPriority {
        Low = 1,
        Normal = 2,
        High = 3,
        Urgent = 4,
    }

    impl PartialOrd for OrderPriority {
        fn partial_cmp(&self, other: &Self) -> Option<std::cmp::Ordering> {
            Some(self.cmp(other))
        }
    }

    impl Ord for OrderPriority {
        fn cmp(&self, other: &Self) -> std::cmp::Ordering {
            (*self as u8).cmp(&(*other as u8))
        }
    }

    #[derive(Debug, Clone)]
    struct PriorityOrder {
        id: u32,
        customer: String,
        items: Vec<String>,
        priority: OrderPriority,
        estimated_time: u32, // minutes
    }

    impl PriorityOrder {
        fn new(id: u32, customer: String, items: Vec<String>, priority: OrderPriority, estimated_time: u32) -> Self {
            PriorityOrder {
                id,
                customer,
                items,
                priority,
                estimated_time,
            }
        }
    }

    // Custom priority queue implementation
    struct OrderPriorityQueue {
        orders: Vec<PriorityOrder>,
    }

    impl OrderPriorityQueue {
        fn new() -> Self {
            OrderPriorityQueue {
                orders: Vec::new(),
            }
        }

        fn enqueue(&mut self, order: PriorityOrder) {
            // Insert order maintaining priority order (highest priority first)
            let mut insert_pos = self.orders.len();

            for (i, existing_order) in self.orders.iter().enumerate() {
                if order.priority > existing_order.priority {
                    insert_pos = i;
                    break;
                }
            }

            println!("     üìù Queued order {} with {:?} priority at position {}",
                     order.id, order.priority, insert_pos);
            self.orders.insert(insert_pos, order);
        }

        fn dequeue(&mut self) -> Option<PriorityOrder> {
            if self.orders.is_empty() {
                None
            } else {
                let order = self.orders.remove(0);
                println!("     üçΩÔ∏è Dequeued order {} ({:?} priority)", order.id, order.priority);
                Some(order)
            }
        }

        fn peek(&self) -> Option<&PriorityOrder> {
            self.orders.first()
        }

        fn len(&self) -> usize {
            self.orders.len()
        }

        fn display_queue(&self) {
            println!("     üìã Current order queue:");
            for (i, order) in self.orders.iter().enumerate() {
                println!("       {}: Order {} - {} ({:?}) - {}min",
                         i + 1, order.id, order.customer, order.priority, order.estimated_time);
            }
        }
    }

    // Demonstrate priority queue
    let mut order_queue = OrderPriorityQueue::new();

    // Add orders with different priorities
    order_queue.enqueue(PriorityOrder::new(
        101, "John Doe".to_string(),
        vec!["Pizza".to_string()], OrderPriority::Normal, 15
    ));

    order_queue.enqueue(PriorityOrder::new(
        102, "VIP Customer".to_string(),
        vec!["Steak".to_string()], OrderPriority::Urgent, 25
    ));

    order_queue.enqueue(PriorityOrder::new(
        103, "Regular Customer".to_string(),
        vec!["Salad".to_string()], OrderPriority::Low, 10
    ));

    order_queue.enqueue(PriorityOrder::new(
        104, "Important Client".to_string(),
        vec!["Pasta".to_string()], OrderPriority::High, 18
    ));

    order_queue.display_queue();

    // Process orders by priority
    println!("   üçΩÔ∏è Processing orders by priority:");
    while order_queue.len() > 0 {
        if let Some(order) = order_queue.dequeue() {
            println!("     ‚ö° Processing: {} for {} ({}min)",
                     order.items.join(", "), order.customer, order.estimated_time);
        }
    }

    // Application 2: Inventory Management with Multi-Level Storage
    println!("\n2Ô∏è‚É£ Application: Multi-Level Inventory Management");

    #[derive(Debug, Clone)]
    struct InventoryItem {
        id: String,
        name: String,
        quantity: u32,
        unit: String,
        location: String,
    }

    impl InventoryItem {
        fn new(id: String, name: String, quantity: u32, unit: String, location: String) -> Self {
            InventoryItem { id, name, quantity, unit, location }
        }
    }

    // Multi-level inventory system
    struct InventorySystem {
        // Primary storage: HashMap for O(1) lookup by ID
        items_by_id: HashMap<String, InventoryItem>,
        // Secondary index: HashMap of location -> Vec of item IDs
        items_by_location: HashMap<String, Vec<String>>,
        // Tertiary index: HashMap of name -> Vec of item IDs (for searching)
        items_by_name: HashMap<String, Vec<String>>,
        // Recent activity log (using VecDeque for efficient push/pop)
        activity_log: VecDeque<String>,
        max_log_size: usize,
    }

    impl InventorySystem {
        fn new(max_log_size: usize) -> Self {
            InventorySystem {
                items_by_id: HashMap::new(),
                items_by_location: HashMap::new(),
                items_by_name: HashMap::new(),
                activity_log: VecDeque::new(),
                max_log_size,
            }
        }

        fn add_item(&mut self, item: InventoryItem) {
            let activity = format!("Added {} {} of {} at {}",
                                 item.quantity, item.unit, item.name, item.location);

            // Add to primary storage
            self.items_by_id.insert(item.id.clone(), item.clone());

            // Add to location index
            self.items_by_location
                .entry(item.location.clone())
                .or_insert_with(Vec::new)
                .push(item.id.clone());

            // Add to name index
            self.items_by_name
                .entry(item.name.clone())
                .or_insert_with(Vec::new)
                .push(item.id.clone());

            // Log activity
            self.log_activity(activity);

            println!("     üì¶ Added inventory item: {} at {}", item.name, item.location);
        }

        fn get_item(&self, id: &str) -> Option<&InventoryItem> {
            self.items_by_id.get(id)
        }

        fn get_items_by_location(&self, location: &str) -> Vec<&InventoryItem> {
            self.items_by_location
                .get(location)
                .map(|ids| {
                    ids.iter()
                        .filter_map(|id| self.items_by_id.get(id))
                        .collect()
                })
                .unwrap_or_default()
        }

        fn search_by_name(&self, name: &str) -> Vec<&InventoryItem> {
            self.items_by_name
                .get(name)
                .map(|ids| {
                    ids.iter()
                        .filter_map(|id| self.items_by_id.get(id))
                        .collect()
                })
                .unwrap_or_default()
        }

        fn update_quantity(&mut self, id: &str, new_quantity: u32) -> Result<(), String> {
            match self.items_by_id.get_mut(id) {
                Some(item) => {
                    let old_quantity = item.quantity;
                    item.quantity = new_quantity;

                    let activity = format!("Updated {} quantity: {} -> {} {}",
                                         item.name, old_quantity, new_quantity, item.unit);
                    self.log_activity(activity);

                    println!("     üìä Updated {}: {} -> {} {}",
                             item.name, old_quantity, new_quantity, item.unit);
                    Ok(())
                }
                None => Err(format!("Item {} not found", id)),
            }
        }

        fn log_activity(&mut self, activity: String) {
            if self.activity_log.len() >= self.max_log_size {
                self.activity_log.pop_front();
            }
            self.activity_log.push_back(activity);
        }

        fn get_recent_activity(&self, count: usize) -> Vec<&String> {
            self.activity_log
                .iter()
                .rev()
                .take(count)
                .collect()
        }

        fn get_statistics(&self) -> (usize, usize, usize) {
            let total_items = self.items_by_id.len();
            let locations = self.items_by_location.len();
            let unique_names = self.items_by_name.len();
            (total_items, locations, unique_names)
        }
    }

    // Demonstrate inventory system
    let mut inventory = InventorySystem::new(10);

    // Add various items
    inventory.add_item(InventoryItem::new(
        "TOMATO001".to_string(), "Fresh Tomatoes".to_string(),
        50, "kg".to_string(), "Cold Storage A".to_string()
    ));

    inventory.add_item(InventoryItem::new(
        "PASTA001".to_string(), "Spaghetti".to_string(),
        25, "boxes".to_string(), "Dry Storage B".to_string()
    ));

    inventory.add_item(InventoryItem::new(
        "TOMATO002".to_string(), "Canned Tomatoes".to_string(),
        100, "cans".to_string(), "Dry Storage B".to_string()
    ));

    inventory.add_item(InventoryItem::new(
        "CHEESE001".to_string(), "Mozzarella".to_string(),
        15, "kg".to_string(), "Cold Storage A".to_string()
    ));

    // Demonstrate different access patterns
    println!("   üìä Inventory system demonstration:");

    // Lookup by ID
    if let Some(item) = inventory.get_item("TOMATO001") {
        println!("     üîç Found by ID: {} - {} {}", item.name, item.quantity, item.unit);
    }

    // Search by location
    let cold_storage_items = inventory.get_items_by_location("Cold Storage A");
    println!("     üè™ Cold Storage A contains {} items:", cold_storage_items.len());
    for item in cold_storage_items {
        println!("       - {}: {} {}", item.name, item.quantity, item.unit);
    }

    // Search by name pattern
    let tomato_products = inventory.search_by_name("Fresh Tomatoes");
    println!("     üçÖ Fresh Tomatoes found: {} items", tomato_products.len());

    // Update quantities
    inventory.update_quantity("PASTA001", 20).ok();
    inventory.update_quantity("CHEESE001", 12).ok();

    // Show recent activity
    println!("     üìã Recent activity:");
    let recent = inventory.get_recent_activity(3);
    for (i, activity) in recent.iter().enumerate() {
        println!("       {}. {}", i + 1, activity);
    }

    // Show statistics
    let (total, locations, names) = inventory.get_statistics();
    println!("     üìà System stats: {} items, {} locations, {} unique names",
             total, locations, names);

    // Application 3: Customer Relationship Management
    println!("\n3Ô∏è‚É£ Application: Customer Relationship Graph");

    #[derive(Debug, Clone)]
    struct Customer {
        id: u32,
        name: String,
        email: String,
        phone: String,
        total_orders: u32,
        total_spent: f64,
    }

    impl Customer {
        fn new(id: u32, name: String, email: String, phone: String) -> Self {
            Customer {
                id, name, email, phone,
                total_orders: 0,
                total_spent: 0.0,
            }
        }
    }

    // Customer relationship management system using graph-like structure
    struct CRMSystem {
        customers: HashMap<u32, Rc<RefCell<Customer>>>,
        email_index: HashMap<String, u32>,
        phone_index: HashMap<String, u32>,
        referrals: HashMap<u32, Vec<u32>>, // customer_id -> referred customer_ids
        order_history: HashMap<u32, VecDeque<(String, f64)>>, // customer_id -> order history
    }

    impl CRMSystem {
        fn new() -> Self {
            CRMSystem {
                customers: HashMap::new(),
                email_index: HashMap::new(),
                phone_index: HashMap::new(),
                referrals: HashMap::new(),
                order_history: HashMap::new(),
            }
        }

        fn add_customer(&mut self, customer: Customer) {
            let customer_id = customer.id;
            let email = customer.email.clone();
            let phone = customer.phone.clone();

            let customer_rc = Rc::new(RefCell::new(customer));

            // Add to primary storage
            self.customers.insert(customer_id, customer_rc);

            // Add to indices
            self.email_index.insert(email, customer_id);
            self.phone_index.insert(phone, customer_id);

            // Initialize empty order history
            self.order_history.insert(customer_id, VecDeque::new());

            println!("     üë§ Added customer ID {}", customer_id);
        }

        fn find_by_email(&self, email: &str) -> Option<Rc<RefCell<Customer>>> {
            self.email_index
                .get(email)
                .and_then(|id| self.customers.get(id))
                .cloned()
        }

        fn add_referral(&mut self, referrer_id: u32, referred_id: u32) {
            self.referrals
                .entry(referrer_id)
                .or_insert_with(Vec::new)
                .push(referred_id);

            println!("     ü§ù Customer {} referred customer {}", referrer_id, referred_id);
        }

        fn add_order(&mut self, customer_id: u32, order_description: String, amount: f64) {
            // Update customer statistics
            if let Some(customer_rc) = self.customers.get(&customer_id) {
                let mut customer = customer_rc.borrow_mut();
                customer.total_orders += 1;
                customer.total_spent += amount;
            }

            // Add to order history
            if let Some(history) = self.order_history.get_mut(&customer_id) {
                history.push_back((order_description.clone(), amount));

                // Keep only last 10 orders
                if history.len() > 10 {
                    history.pop_front();
                }
            }

            println!("     üí∞ Customer {} placed order: {} (${:.2})",
                     customer_id, order_description, amount);
        }

        fn get_referrals(&self, customer_id: u32) -> Vec<Rc<RefCell<Customer>>> {
            self.referrals
                .get(&customer_id)
                .map(|referred_ids| {
                    referred_ids
                        .iter()
                        .filter_map(|id| self.customers.get(id))
                        .cloned()
                        .collect()
                })
                .unwrap_or_default()
        }

        fn get_customer_summary(&self, customer_id: u32) -> Option<String> {
            self.customers.get(&customer_id).map(|customer_rc| {
                let customer = customer_rc.borrow();
                let order_count = self.order_history
                    .get(&customer_id)
                    .map(|h| h.len())
                    .unwrap_or(0);

                format!("{} - {} orders, ${:.2} spent, {} recent orders in history",
                       customer.name, customer.total_orders, customer.total_spent, order_count)
            })
        }
    }

    // Demonstrate CRM system
    let mut crm = CRMSystem::new();

    // Add customers
    crm.add_customer(Customer::new(
        1001, "Alice Johnson".to_string(),
        "alice@email.com".to_string(), "555-0101".to_string()
    ));

    crm.add_customer(Customer::new(
        1002, "Bob Smith".to_string(),
        "bob@email.com".to_string(), "555-0102".to_string()
    ));

    crm.add_customer(Customer::new(
        1003, "Carol Davis".to_string(),
        "carol@email.com".to_string(), "555-0103".to_string()
    ));

    // Add referral relationships
    crm.add_referral(1001, 1002); // Alice referred Bob
    crm.add_referral(1001, 1003); // Alice referred Carol

    // Add order history
    crm.add_order(1001, "Pizza and Salad".to_string(), 28.99);
    crm.add_order(1001, "Pasta Dinner".to_string(), 22.50);
    crm.add_order(1002, "Burger Combo".to_string(), 15.99);
    crm.add_order(1003, "Sushi Platter".to_string(), 35.00);

    println!("   üë• CRM system demonstration:");

    // Find customer by email
    if let Some(customer_rc) = crm.find_by_email("alice@email.com") {
        let customer = customer_rc.borrow();
        println!("     üìß Found by email: {} (ID: {})", customer.name, customer.id);
    }

    // Show referrals
    let referrals = crm.get_referrals(1001);
    println!("     ü§ù Alice's referrals: {} customers", referrals.len());
    for referral in referrals {
        let customer = referral.borrow();
        println!("       - {} (ID: {})", customer.name, customer.id);
    }

    // Show customer summaries
    for customer_id in [1001, 1002, 1003] {
        if let Some(summary) = crm.get_customer_summary(customer_id) {
            println!("     üìä Customer {}: {}", customer_id, summary);
        }
    }

    println!("\nüéØ Real-World Data Structure Benefits:");
    println!("   ‚ö° Priority queues enable efficient order processing by importance");
    println!("   üìä Multi-level indices provide O(1) lookup with multiple access patterns");
    println!("   üï∏Ô∏è Graph-like structures model complex business relationships");
    println!("   üíæ Automatic memory management prevents leaks in complex systems");
    println!("   üîÑ Interior mutability enables flexible shared state management");

    println!("\nüí° Professional Implementation Guidelines:");
    println!("   üéØ Choose data structures based on access patterns and performance needs");
    println!("   üìã Use multiple indices for different query types");
    println!("   üîó Leverage Rc/RefCell for shared ownership with interior mutability");
    println!("   üìù Implement bounded collections to prevent memory growth");
    println!("   üß™ Test with realistic data volumes and usage patterns");
}

fn main() {
    demonstrate_real_world_applications();

## Summary and Key Takeaways

### **Mental Model: The Complete Professional Restaurant Storage System Design**

Remember our comprehensive professional restaurant storage system analogy:

- üèóÔ∏è **Custom data structures** = **Specialized storage solutions** - Purpose-built systems for specific operational needs
- üõ°Ô∏è **Memory safety** = **Safe storage management** - Automatic tracking and cleanup prevents corruption and loss
- üì¶ **Ownership system** = **Clear resource responsibility** - Every item has exactly one responsible manager
- üöÄ **Advanced patterns** = **Sophisticated architectures** - Professional-grade systems for complex requirements
- üíº **Real-world applications** = **Complete operational systems** - Integrated solutions handling all business needs


### **Essential Data Structure Components in Rust**

**Core Building Blocks:**

- **Structs** - Define custom data types with named fields
- **Enums** - Represent data that can be one of several variants
- **Box<T>** - Heap allocation for recursive structures and large data
- **Option<T>** - Safe representation of values that may or may not exist
- **Vec<T>** - Growable array for dynamic collections
- **HashMap<K,V>** - Hash table for key-value associations

**Memory Management Tools:**

- **Ownership** - Each value has exactly one owner responsible for cleanup
- **Borrowing** - Temporary access without ownership transfer
- **Reference Counting (Rc<T>)** - Shared ownership for multiple references
- **Interior Mutability (RefCell<T>)** - Mutable access through shared references
- **Weak References** - Non-owning references that prevent cycles


### **Implementation Patterns and Best Practices**

**‚úÖ Safe Structure Design:**

```rust
// Use Option for optional connections
struct Node<T> {
    data: T,
    next: Option<Box<Node<T>>>, // Safe recursive structure
}

// Use generic types for reusability
struct Container<T> {
    items: Vec<T>,
    capacity: usize,
}
```

**‚úÖ Memory Safety Patterns:**

```rust
// Automatic cleanup with Drop
impl<T> Drop for MyStructure<T> {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        println!("Cleaning up resources");
    }
}

// Safe ownership transfer
fn transfer_ownership<T>(item: T) -> Box<T> {
    Box::new(item)
}
```

**‚úÖ Shared Ownership When Needed:**

```rust
use std::rc::{Rc, Weak};
use std::cell::RefCell;

// Shared ownership without cycles
struct Parent {
    children: Vec<Rc<Child>>,
}
struct Child {
    parent: Weak<Parent>, // Prevents cycles
}
```


### **Performance and Design Considerations**

| **Pattern** | **Use Case** | **Performance** | **Complexity** |
| :-- | :-- | :-- | :-- |
| **Vec<T>** | Dynamic arrays, stacks | O(1) append, O(n) insert | Low |
| **HashMap<K,V>** | Key-value lookup | O(1) average access | Medium |
| **Linked List** | Frequent insertion/deletion | O(1) at ends, O(n) random | Medium |
| **Tree Structures** | Hierarchical data | O(log n) search | High |
| **Graph Structures** | Complex relationships | Varies by algorithm | High |

### **Professional Best Practices Checklist**

**‚úÖ Design Guidelines:**

- Start with simple structures and add complexity only when needed
- Use generics to make structures reusable across different data types
- Implement Drop trait for custom cleanup of external resources
- Design APIs that leverage Rust's ownership system naturally

**‚úÖ Memory Management Guidelines:**

- Prefer owned data (Box, Vec, String) over borrowed data for structure fields
- Use Rc<RefCell<T>> for shared mutable state when necessary
- Use Weak references to break potential reference cycles
- Plan memory allocation patterns to avoid unnecessary heap usage

**‚úÖ Performance Guidelines:**

- Choose data structures based on actual access patterns
- Use multiple indices for different query types
- Implement bounded collections to prevent unbounded memory growth
- Profile with realistic data sizes and usage patterns

**‚ùå Common Pitfalls:**

- Creating reference cycles with Rc without using Weak
- Overusing RefCell and interior mutability when not needed
- Not implementing proper error handling for structure operations
- Designing structures that fight against Rust's ownership model
- Not considering the memory layout and cache performance implications
